FREE MEALS ARE BACK!

Owatonna Public Schools Nutrition Services will be offering meals at NO COST to ALL CHILDREN ages 1-18 regardless of income.

Free meals will be available starting Monday, September 14, 2020 through December 31st, 2020 or until USDA funding is exhausted.

For more information, please visit our website:
https://www.isd761.org/district-services/nutrition-services/welcome

post_text:
It's #TeacherFeature Friday!

"Hello! I am Alexa Olson.

I am a second-grade teacher at Washington Elementary. I am going on 4 years of teaching in OPS.

I grew up here in Owatonna and had the privilege to attend OPS myself. I love calling Owatonna home! I have a small family of four, me, my fiance, Matthew, and our two fur babies, Oakley and Lulu. This Fall we made a special addition to our family adding Lulu. We are so excited to add more cuteness to our family!

It is such an exciting year for us my fiance and I will also be getting married this spring and I am so excited to become Mrs. Simon!

I love spending time with my family and friends, going for walks with our pups, spending time outside and being crafty.

I love working for OPS because I get to make a difference and inspire students to be the best they can be. I enjoy loving and supporting our Owatonna students each and every day!!"

#OwatonnaProud

Be part of the #OwatonnaProud team!!

We have up to 3 custodial positions available.

Summary of our custodial positions: The Custodian performs semi-skilled work cleaning and maintaining school building interiors and exteriors as well as grounds and related work as apparent or assigned to ensure a safe and pleasant appearance of school district buildings and grounds.

Hours/Schedule:
8 hours per day / 3:00 PM - 11:30 PM / 5 days per week / Monday - Friday

Classification/Pay Rate:
A-1-2 / $13.69 - $15.76 per hour
A-1-3 / $14.78 - $17.04 per hour

Applicants can apply online or view our open positions at https://www.isd761.org/careers

post_text:
We are looking for Health Office Nurses!

Position Summary:
Provide care within the school setting including administering medications, providing first aid services and maintaining health records under the supervision of a licensed professional nurse.

Position Requirements:
High school diploma. Graduate of an accredited school of nursing and Minnesota LPN or RN licensure. Certification in CPR and basic First Aid. Consistent and reliable attendance.

Part-Time / Full-time / Long term Substitute needed.

Full-Time Hours/Schedule:
6.5 hours per day (7:45 am - 2:45 pm) / 5 days per week / 180 days per year

Part-Time Hours/Schedule:
5.75 hours per day (7:45 am - 2:00pm) / 5 days per week / 180 days per year

Could you be part of our #OwatonnaProud team?

post_text:
It is time for #TeacherFearture Friday! Today let's welcome Jake Jensen!

"Hello! My name is Jake Jensen, and I get to teach sixth and seventh grade science at Owatonna Middle School this coming school year!

I grew up in Owatonna and graduated in 2013. I grew up loving this community and I saw the impact my grandparents made in the community as teachers here, and their example has brought me down a similar path.

I graduated from Bemidji State University with a Bachelor’s degree in science education in 2017. This spring I graduated from Saint Mary’s University of Minnesota with a Masters of Education.

My first three years of teaching were in Sauk Rapids-Rice, where I was fortunate enough to be the head cross country coach. I am proud to bring my learning and experience here, to grow as a teacher and work for this great community!

On the side I love reading fiction, spending my days on a lake, and losing myself for hours on the pottery wheel.

I look forward to meeting you!"

#OwatonnaProud

post_text:
Please help us welcome Maggie Goldade to the #OwatonnaProud team!

"Hello, my name is Maggie Goldade and I am thrilled to be joining the Owatonna team in “Inspiring Excellence. Every Learner, Every Day.”

I started my role as Special Services Supervisor in July, supporting Early Childhood Special Education (ECSE) and Elementary programs. I’ve been inspired by the district’s commitment to equity, social development, and creative problem solving to meet the needs of diverse learners.

Most recently, I worked for Prior Lake-Savage Area Schools, as a B-3 ECSE teacher and Special Education Team Lead at Edgewood Early Childhood and La Ola Del Lago Spanish Immersion Elementary School. Prior to that, I was an ECSE teacher in Northfield.

I live in New Prague with my husband, Matthew, and our three girls, Elsie (9), Cora (7), and Alaina (5). We enjoy playing games, cards, gardening and going for bike rides or walks.

I'm looking forward to the start of the 2020-21 school year!"

post_text:
Please join us in welcoming Meghan Hendricks to the #OwatonnaProud team!

"Hi, I’m Meghan Hendricks and I am a new speech-language pathologist for the Owatonna School District working with preschool!

I’m originally from Jordan, MN. I completed my undergraduate degree at University of North Dakota and my graduate degree from Minnesota State University, Mankato for Communication Sciences and Disorders. As a teen I saw an SLP for a tongue thrust I developed, so I have been both the client and the clinician in speech therapy!

Some fun facts about me are that I have double jointed elbows, I get a mustache of freckles in the summertime, and I am going to be an aunt for the first time in October!

I’m beyond excited to start my journey with the Owatonna School District and have a great school year."

post_text:
Welcome to this Friday's #TeacherFeature!

"I'm Mitch Dinse the Industrial Technology teacher at OHS.

Before coming to Owatonna, I was an agriculture and industrial technology teacher for two years at Triton Public Schools in Dodge Center.

I am the middle child of the family. My dad is a crop farmer in western Steele County. My mom is a third grade teacher at Wilson Elementary in Owatonna. I have an older brother and sister in law that live in Sioux Falls, SD and a younger sister that just graduated from OHS and will be starting college at SDSU this fall. I live on a farm and love the country lifestyle that comes with it. Fishing, sports, livestock, and being outdoors are some of my favorite hobbies.

I am an Owatonna grad, graduating from OHS in 2014 and I graduated from UW-River Falls in the fall of 2018. It has always been a goal of mine to come back to my hometown to teach and build new relationships with students and staff. Owatonna is a community that I love and I can't wait to wear the blue and silver once again! Go Huskies!"

#OwatonnaProud

post_text:
Let's give a warm welcome to Makayla Kunkel!

"Hello! My name is Makayla Kunkel, and this year I will be a fourth and fifth grade EL Teacher at McKinley Elementary.

I am from Rochester and I went to college at Minnesota State University, Mankato. I was placed in second grade at McKinley Elementary in 2018 for student teaching, and instantly fell in love with Owatonna Public Schools.

After completing my year-long student teaching, I became a district-wide substitute teacher. I worked in a wide variety of classrooms- everything from preschool to middle school band! It was an incredible experience to work in all the buildings and form relationships with so many students and staff. This last year I was a fifth-grade teacher at Wilson Elementary- shoutout to 5D!

I feel so lucky to work in this district and I love all the relationships I have built. I am proud to be a member of Owatonna Public Schools. Go Huskies!"

#OwatonnaProud

Let's welcome Lincoln Elementary's new Speech-Language Pathologist!

"Hi, my name is Ashley Schaefer and I will be joining Lincoln Elementary as a speech-language pathologist!

A little bit about myself, I am originally from Glencoe, Minnesota and am a new graduate of Minnesota State University - Mankato. I love to read, stay active with biking, hiking, or exercising, and spend time with my cat, Gracie!

I have a strong background in child speech and language development as well as linguistic and literacy intervention. I have always had a passion for working with children and helping them to feel successful and confident in themselves.

I'm thrilled to be joining the Owatonna Public Schools team!"

The custodian performs semi-skilled work cleaning and maintaining school building interiors and exteriors as well as grounds and related work as apparent or assigned to ensure a safe and pleasant appearance of school district buildings and grounds.

Hours/Schedule:
8 hours per day / 3:00 PM - 11:30 PM / 5 days per week / Monday - Friday

Applicants can apply online or view our open positions at https://www.isd761.org/careers

post_text:
Did you know that voter-approved funding to build or repair school buildings is a legally separate pot of money from voter-approved funding to operate schools and pay teachers?

Both are critical parts of providing a quality education for our students, but bond funds (what Owatonna residents approved for our new high school last fall) can’t be used to pay for school operations.

Learn more about how Owatonna Schools are working hard to provide a solid financial foundation for our students and our schools here: https://www.isd761.org/our-district/finance-facts

#OwatonnaProud

At the June 22 school board meeting, Superintendent Jeff Elstad recognized the 2nd-grade team at McKinley Elementary (Valerie Seath, Katie Demmer, Kate Seifert, and Lori Huisenga) whose classes created a non-fiction digital animal book during distance learning that was acknowledged by Highlights magazine CEO and chief editor!

This project involved second-grade students collaborating through distance learning on creating a magazine with non-fiction text, art, and science information about native Minnesota animals. The students used technology and worked collaboratively through Google classroom.

Check out the video from Highlights to the 2nd Grade McKinley Elementary Class: https://vimeo.com/418411216

#OwatonnaProud

"Without Success Coaches we would miss a vital link to and from our multilingual families. I'm constantly humbled and reminded how amazing this group is to our community."
~Dr. Martina Wagner, EL Coordinator

Success Coaches serve as liaisons between multilingual families/students and school sites to help develop and sustain a trusting and supportive relationship that will benefit students, families, and the district. Thank you, Success Coaches, for inspiring excellence, every day!

#OwatonnaProud

Pictured left to right: Ana Alvarez, Melina Caballero, Khadra Muhidin, Antonieta Sanchez-Mendez, Muna Hersi, Nura Elmi, and Hussein Osman (not pictured: Sylvia Zavala)

post_text:
Congratulations to Landon for completing Book 1 for Trumpet during virtual lessons Friday!

Landon has been a consistently hard-worker, and virtual instruction did not get in the way of his focus and drive for learning the trumpet.

Recently, Landon completed the last exercise in Book 1 for Trumpet playing the melody from "Manhatten Beach March" by John Philip Sousa.

Landon's accomplishments this school year are a testament to his hard work: He was chosen for the MN Middle Level Honor Band and the MBDA Beginner Honor Band (both which were unfortunately canceled due to the pandemic) and was also scheduled to play a solo with the high school band this spring.

Despite the cancellations, Landon holds a positive attitude and work ethic. Look for more great music to happen in Landon's future!

#OwatonnaProud

post_text:
It's time for #TeacherFeature Friday!

"I am Jess Wagner.

I started teaching at OHS in 2002. During that time I have taught 9-12, journalism, public speaking, and elective literature classes. I also coached the OHS Speech team for 10 years.

Seven years ago, I became the adviser of OHS Magnet. My students made the move from print to online over the years. They have published OHS news and multi-media that has been recognized for excellence at the state and national levels.

I love coming to work at Owatonna Public Schools. I love the daily conversations and laughter that fill my day with my kids. My colleagues are amazing teachers and friends!

I am more of "work behind the scenes type of person", so the "Wagner Appreciation Week" is a little out of my comfort zone. I am humbled by the kindness and this honor from the Owatonna Teachers. This year especially has been tough and I believe all teachers are the teacher of the year."

Your kindness is inspiring and we are honored to have you on our #OwatonnaProud team!

post_text:
Gooooooooooooooood morning OMS!

Attached is an image of Checkpoint # 3. We are half-way through our #OMSRacetheUS. It's going to require a big push by everyone to complete the entire loop of the United States before June 1. Currently, the staff is holding a strong lead despite the disparity in staff to student ratio.

Who's in it to win it? It's exciting to see that we have our top 5 "mileagers" attached for both staff and students. Great work!

We have had 85 staff participate and 120 students. It looks like students, you might want to start spreading the word on social media!

Miles can be logged at bit.ly/omsracestudent

post_text:
Welcome to this week's #TeacherFeature Friday!

"My name is Sara Awe and I enjoy being a 3rd Grade teacher at Washington. This is my 20th year of teaching for Owatonna! Prior to this year, I taught Kindergarten at Washington, so some of my lucky students have had the “awe”some experience of having me twice!

I live with my family (Jeff, Delaney (13), Alexie (10), and Leyton (7) ) in beautiful Mantorville, MN. I have a cat (Chloe) and a pet rabbit (Ninja).

Together, we love to travel on vacations, and I love watching all 3 busy children play on lots of sports teams. I love the summer, being outside, and reading. Besides cheering for my own kids, I love cheering on the MN United and MN Twins."

Thank you, Mrs. Awe, for being a wonderful addition to our #OwatonnaProud team!

"My name is Sara Awe and I enjoy being a 3rd Grade teacher at Washington. This is my 20th year of teaching for Owatonna! Prior to this year, I taught Kindergarten at Washington, so some of my lucky students have had the “awe”some experience of having me twice!

I live with my family (Jeff, Delaney (13), Alexie (10), and Leyton (7) ) in beautiful Mantorville, MN. I have a cat (Chloe) and a pet rabbit (Ninja).

Together, we love to travel on vacations, and I love watching all 3 busy children play on lots of sports teams. I love the summer, being outside, and reading. Besides cheering for my own kids, I love cheering on the MN United and MN Twins."

Thank you, Mrs. Awe, for being a wonderful addition to our #OwatonnaProud team!

The race is on!

OMS staff have challenged our student body to an OMS Virtual race around the United States. Staff and students can log miles via bike, walk, run, scooter, skateboard.

There are different check-ins every 5 days to track progress. The route goes from OMS to Cleveland, to Bangor (Maine), Hilton Head (SC), Houston (TX), Sacramento (CA), Seattle (WA), Bozeman (MT), back to OMS.

Let's get out and log those miles!

#OwatonnaProud

post_text:
Today is School Lunch Hero Day! We would like to take a moment to thank all of our front line Nutrition Services heroes. Through the snow and the rain, our Nutrition Services professionals have dedicated themselves to serving meals during the COVID-19 School Closure. Thanks to their effort, over 41,000 free meals have been served to children ages 1-18 since March 18th. None of this would be possible without them. THANK YOU!

If you would like to show your appreciation for our School Lunch Heros, they would love to hear from you! Comment below, share a picture enjoying your meals, make a sign, shout out thank you, or do anything that lets them know how much of a difference they make.

For more information about our free meals for children during the COVID-19 School Closure, please visit our website https://www.owatonna.k12.mn.us/page/3750

Welcome to this Friday's #TeacherFeature!

"I am Anissa Williams, a Kindergarten teacher at Wilson Elementary.

I have taught for 22 years. Seven years in the Kasson Mantorville District and 15 years in OPS.

I have a husband, Josh, who is also employed as a Physical Education teacher and basketball coach in the district. We have three teenagers, Kinzie is 19, Brayden is 16, and Leyton is 14.

I enjoy being with family, running, spending time at the lake, and helping families with healthy meals.

I love working for OPS because I aid and inspire our youngest learners by laying a strong foundation for their education."

We love that you are part of our #OwatonnaProud staff!

It's time for #TeacherFeature Friday!

"My name is Kara Fradet and I am a first-grade teacher at Washington. I have taught 1 year in 2nd grade and 6 years in first grade in Owatonna. Previously, I taught 3rd grade for 5 years in Bullhead City, AZ.

I originally grew up in Moorhead, MN.

In my free time, I enjoy spending time with my family and friends, reading, watching movies, and taking walks with my dog, Mickey.

Working with my students, their families, my colleagues, and the Owatonna community makes me feel like I am part of an amazing village filled with support, encouragement, growth, and love. There is nowhere I would rather be!"

We're so glad you're part of our #OwatonnaProud family!

A heartfelt thank you goes out to all our #OwatonnaProud students and families for doing such a great job transitioning to distance learning.

This special message from Mrs. Nelson to her fifth graders could certainly apply to students of all ages!

"I cannot tell you how proud I am of my students for their participation and positive attitude! Each morning we use Google Meet and get the chance to start our day together-just like "normal". They always show up and are ready for a great but "distant" learning opportunity! I love them!"

post_text:
Congratulations to Logan Norrid, Owatonna High School 9th grade student as she set a new Owatonna Girls Swimming record in the 100 Fly with a time of 57.68 and in the 200 IM with a time of 2:10:00.

Norrid placed first in the Section 1AA meet in the 100 Fly and second in the 200 IM. She will be competing in both events at the MSHSL Girls Swim and Dive Championships on Friday, Nov. 15 (Prelims) and Saturday, Nov. 16 (Finals). The meet will be located at Jean Freeman Aquatic Center, U of M.

For information on the 2019 State Girls' Swim and Dive Championships visit:
https://www.owatonna.k12.mn.us/page/hot_news/view/366

Congratulations and Best of luck Logan!

Today the STRIVE (Students Taking a Renewed Interest in the Value of Education) program started. STRIVE is a mentoring program where a Rotary Club of Owatonna member is matched with a OHS senior student to assist the student in discovering their own strengths and talents to increase their personal and academic achievement. Thank you to all of our Rotary mentors and STRIVE students... it's going to be a great year!

post_text:
Lincoln Elementary Has Heart

Written by Auden and Nicolina from 5RO

Every year our art teacher Mrs. Dutton has us do a collaborative art project, which means that the whole school does an art project in all different ways. This year she came up with the idea of having our whole school do a heart project because she was kids being rude to one another. She wanted to put up a big reminder all over the school to always be kind and not to bully because of their differences.

The individual heart squares are 5 inches by 5 inches. Kindergartners did kiwik stick, 1st graders did crayon batik, 2nd graders did chalk, 3rd graders did watercolors with salt, 4th graders did sharpie design with watercolor, 5th graders did tempera paint.

Now that she is done, she will put them together on a big poster board to make it look like quilt. There will be enough for six boards and she will spread them out all over the school.

#owatonnaproud #inspiringexcellence
Owatonna People's Press Lincoln Elementary School

Now that she is done, she will put them together on a big poster board to make it look like quilt. There will be enough for six boards and she will spread them out all over the school.

Tune in to watch the first #AllWomanSpacewalk! Starting at approximately 7:50 a.m. EDT on Friday, Oct. 18, NASA Astronauts Christina Koch and Jessica Meir will set their spacesuits to battery power before venturing outside of the International Space Station for a 5.5 hour spacewalk. The duo will work in the vacuum of space to replace a power controller that failed over the weekend. Watch:
